Dialogue: 0,2:05:43.53,2:05:46.17,英文,,0,0,0,,Whereas in Scratch, you could repeat three times like this.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:46.17,2:05:53.00,英文,,0,0,0,,In JavaScript, it's pretty much just like C. The only difference here is that you say let instead of int for an example like this.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:53.00,2:05:59.54,英文,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, if you want to do something forever in Scratch, in JavaScript, just like in C, you say while true in this case.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:59.54,2:06:07.02,英文,,0,0,0,,So this is to say, we're sort of comfortable spending relatively little time on JavaScript, at least for today's purposes, because syntactically,
Dialogue: 0,2:06:07.02,2:06:12.13,英文,,0,0,0,,It's really the same as we've seen before, with maybe a slight variance here or there.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:12.13,2:06:16.81,英文,,0,0,0,,But what's interesting today, arguably, is just what kinds of things you can do with it.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:16.81,2:06:20.53,英文,,0,0,0,,So with that said, what kinds of things can we do?
Dialogue: 0,2:06:20.53,2:06:22.90,英文,,0,0,0,,It all comes back to this picture.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:22.90,2:06:25.46,英文,,0,0,0,,If this is a simple web page on the left.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:25.46,2:06:29.90,英文,,0,0,0,,And this is the corresponding tree, or DOM, document object model on the right.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:29.90,2:06:34.16,英文,,0,0,0,,That is the tree the browser automatically creates in memory, or RAM, for you.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:34.16,2:06:42.47,英文,,0,0,0,,JavaScript is now a proper programming language that lets us dynamically manipulate, like read data from this, change this.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:42.47,2:06:46.13,英文,,0,0,0,,And this is how Google, for instance, implements your inbox.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:46.13,2:06:52.95,英文,,0,0,0,,In your inbox, it's like a table, so tr, tr, tr, tr probably, something like that, or heck, maybe div, div, div, div.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:52.95,2:07:04.84,英文,,0,0,0,,Using JavaScript, any time they realize someone sent you new mail, they can create a new node, a new rectangle in memory, and you, the human, see a new div or a new tr again and again and again.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:04.84,2:07:13.96,英文,,0,0,0,,So with JavaScript, you just have the ability to control the user's experience instead of, like I've been doing, constantly hitting reload in the page to see some new content.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:13.96,2:07:21.34,英文,,0,0,0,,To see some new content, JavaScript can be running 24-7 so that you can actually see all of these changes live.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:21.34,2:07:24.23,英文,,0,0,0,,All right, let's go about writing some JavaScript code now.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:24.23,2:07:33.63,英文,,0,0,0,,Instead of writing it on the server and executing it on the server, we're going to actually use a very common paradigm, whereas JavaScript is actually executed in the browser client side.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:33.63,2:07:49.19,英文,,0,0,0,,That is to say, we can actually start writing some JavaScript code inside of our own .html file so that when a user visits that web page with their browser, not only is the HTML and any CSS downloaded to the user's browser, so is that JavaScript code so that it's executed, indeed,
Dialogue: 0,2:07:49.19,2:07:56.06,英文,,0,0,0,,Client-side on the browser rather than server-side, as has been the case with Python in previous weeks.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:56.06,2:07:58.62,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, where do we go about writing some JavaScript code?
Dialogue: 0,2:07:58.62,2:08:06.48,英文,,0,0,0,,Let's go ahead and revisit hello.html, which previously was a completely static example that literally just said, hello, title, hello, body.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:06.48,2:08:17.01,英文,,0,0,0,,Indeed, if I open this up using HTTP server and view it now in a separate tab, all it said was exactly that, hello, title in the tab, and hello, body in the main part of the viewport, so to speak.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:17.01,2:08:24.22,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, let's make this example a little more dynamic so it doesn't just say, hello, body, but maybe says hello to an actual person.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:24.22,2:08:25.66,英文,,0,0,0,,So let's go ahead and do this.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:25.66,2:08:28.78,英文,,0,0,0,,Let's go ahead and remove the hard-coded hello, body.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:28.78,2:08:32.63,英文,,0,0,0,,And let's actually go ahead here and use a form tag.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:32.63,2:08:38.03,英文,,0,0,0,,But we're not going to use this form in the usual way, whereby the data gets sent all the way back to the server.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:38.03,2:08:41.95,英文,,0,0,0,,We're going to leverage control over this form client-side instead.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:41.95,2:08:45.71,英文,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to go ahead and create this open form tag, close form tag.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:45.71,2:08:55.97,英文,,0,0,0,,Inside of that, let me give myself a text input that's going to have autocomplete equals, quote unquote, off, just to ensure that what I previously typed in my examples doesn't reappear accidentally.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:55.97,2:09:00.49,英文,,0,0,0,,We're going to autofocus it so that the cursor is blinking right there in that text box.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:00.49,2:09:10.62,英文,,0,0,0,,And this time, I'm going to go ahead and give it, how about a placeholder of quote, unquote, name, to make clear that I'm prompting the user for their name.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:10.62,2:09:14.99,英文,,0,0,0,,And then the type of this text box will be the default, or more explicitly here, text.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:14.99,2:09:21.45,英文,,0,0,0,,And then I'm going to have, as we've seen before, a button, the type of which is submit, also our typical default.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:21.45,2:09:23.71,英文,,0,0,0,,And then inside of this button is going to be the label.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:23.71,2:09:28.14,英文,,0,0,0,,How about something like, how about we'll call this greet.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:28.14,2:09:30.26,英文,,0,0,0,,So that's what the button will actually say.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:30.26,2:09:32.92,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, let me actually go back into my browser tab.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:32.92,2:09:34.04,英文,,0,0,0,,Let me reload this page.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:34.04,2:09:43.34,英文,,0,0,0,,And we should now see a relatively simple form, whereby I have the cursor blinking on a text input, prompting the user for their name, and then a greet button that I can click.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:43.34,2:09:50.58,英文,,0,0,0,,But if I click this button now, it's not going to do anything useful, because I haven't written any code to tell the browser what to do when I click that button.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:50.58,2:09:56.23,英文,,0,0,0,,But it turns out there's all sorts of events in the world of JavaScript that you can listen for, so to speak.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:56.23,2:09:58.27,英文,,0,0,0,,In fact, here's just a list of some of them.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:58.27,2:10:13.97,英文,,0,0,0,,Anytime something changes in a form field, anytime the user clicks or drags on something, anytime the user presses a key and maybe lifts their finger up, anytime the mouse goes down or over or up on top of something, or anytime a form is submitted, those are events.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:13.97,2:10:17.79,英文,,0,0,0,,In the same way that we talked about events back in week 0 in Scratch,
Dialogue: 0,2:10:17.79,2:10:27.74,英文,,0,0,0,,And in JavaScript, just like in Scratch, where you can do something when green flag clicked, in JavaScript, you can write code that actually listens for any of these events or more.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:27.74,2:10:32.80,英文,,0,0,0,,So with that said, let's go back to VS Code here, and let's make a couple of changes instead.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:32.80,2:10:35.60,英文,,0,0,0,,Let's go ahead and add to this form a new attribute.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:35.60,2:10:39.12,英文,,0,0,0,,That's not the best way to do it, but it's perhaps the simplest for version 1 here.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:39.12,2:10:42.18,英文,,0,0,0,,And let's say onSubmit do the following.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:42.18,2:10:44.30,英文,,0,0,0,,So onSubmit is an HTML attribute.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:44.30,2:10:50.20,英文,,0,0,0,,And curiously, its value inside of the quotes there can actually be some JavaScript code.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:50.20,2:10:54.70,英文,,0,0,0,,And let's go ahead now, and let's assume there exists a function in the world called greet.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:54.70,2:10:58.44,英文,,0,0,0,,And what I want to do is call that function right then and there.
Dialogue: 0,2:10:58.44,2:11:01.59,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, now in JavaScript, how do I go about making that function exist?
Dialogue: 0,2:11:01.59,2:11:07.75,英文,,0,0,0,,It doesn't come out of the box just like print might or say might in Python or Scratch, respectively.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:07.75,2:11:08.67,英文,,0,0,0,,But I can do this.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:08.67,2:11:10.93,英文,,0,0,0,,Let me go up into the head of this page.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:10.93,2:11:15.78,英文,,0,0,0,,Inside of a script tag here, both open and close, let me actually write some JavaScript code.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:15.78,2:11:20.04,英文,,0,0,0,,And just so it stands out, I'm going to give myself a couple of blank lines, though not strictly necessary.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:20.04,2:11:23.66,英文,,0,0,0,,And let me define a new function in JavaScript called greet.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:23.66,2:11:26.65,英文,,0,0,0,,And this is the syntax in JavaScript for creating your own function.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:26.65,2:11:34.99,英文,,0,0,0,,Similar in Python, instead of saying def in JavaScript, you just say function, then the name of the function and any arguments within the parentheses thereafter.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:34.99,2:11:37.03,英文,,0,0,0,,But I'm not going to pass in any here.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:37.03,2:11:43.12,英文,,0,0,0,,Then inside of curly braces, what I'm going to do is use a built-in JavaScript function that comes with any browser called alert.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:43.12,2:11:45.06,英文,,0,0,0,,It's not the best or prettiest user interface.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:45.06,2:11:47.40,英文,,0,0,0,,But for now, it's going to get the job done.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:47.40,2:11:48.82,英文,,0,0,0,,What do I want to say to the user?
Dialogue: 0,2:11:48.82,2:11:58.87,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, let's first just say something simple like, hello, comma, world, close quote, semicolon, thereby alerting the user with precisely that message.
Dialogue: 0,2:11:58.87,2:12:02.75,英文,,0,0,0,,Now, what I'm going to do down here is make one other change.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:02.75,2:12:07.45,英文,,0,0,0,,I don't want this form to actually get submitted to the server, just like we've seen in the past.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:07.45,2:12:11.63,英文,,0,0,0,,When you submit a form, it often goes to something like google.com slash search.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:11.63,2:12:15.67,英文,,0,0,0,,I actually want my JavaScript code to take control over the entire thing.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:15.67,2:12:27.37,英文,,0,0,0,,The entire user experience of this form so that I'm just using the form as a user input mechanism, not to actually send via GET or POST this data to some other server, including my own.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:27.37,2:12:29.30,英文,,0,0,0,,So this is going to look a little ugly.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:29.30,2:12:33.12,英文,,0,0,0,,But after calling greet, I'm actually going to do this, which I've read the documentation about.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:33.12,2:12:39.74,英文,,0,0,0,,And I know that if you actually hard code return false here, that just tells the browser, please don't actually submit the form.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:39.74,2:12:42.22,英文,,0,0,0,,Only call the greet function.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:42.22,2:12:44.88,英文,,0,0,0,,All right, well, let me go back to my browser here.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:44.88,2:12:49.02,英文,,0,0,0,,Let me reload this, because I need to download the latest version of the JavaScript code.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:49.02,2:12:53.22,英文,,0,0,0,,And I'm just going to go ahead, without even typing my name, I'm going to click on the Greet button.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:53.22,2:12:58.25,英文,,0,0,0,,And you'll see that, albeit a little cryptically at the top, we see an alert that says, hello world.
Dialogue: 0,2:12:58.25,2:13:03.03,英文,,0,0,0,,There's my ugly URL of my code space there at the moment, but we do indeed see that string.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:03.03,2:13:06.35,英文,,0,0,0,,But what I haven't, of course, done is taken any actual name from the user.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:06.35,2:13:08.41,英文,,0,0,0,,So how can we go about doing that?
Dialogue: 0,2:13:08.41,2:13:10.87,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, ideally, I want to alert.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:10.87,2:13:15.99,英文,,0,0,0,,The user with hello, David, or hello, Carter, whatever name I type into that box.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:15.99,2:13:17.90,英文,,0,0,0,,So how can I go about doing that?
Dialogue: 0,2:13:17.90,2:13:19.98,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, let me create a variable called name.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:19.98,2:13:28.27,英文,,0,0,0,,And let me set it equal to this function call, document.querySelector.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:28.27,2:13:30.43,英文,,0,0,0,,That comes with JavaScript itself.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:30.43,2:13:34.87,英文,,0,0,0,,Let me then, in parentheses, pass in an argument that is going to be, huh, the ID.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:34.87,2:13:38.89,英文,,0,0,0,,I need a unique identifier for the thing I want to select.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:38.89,2:13:41.36,英文,,0,0,0,,So let me actually go back to my HTML code here.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:41.36,2:13:50.92,英文,,0,0,0,,And instead of giving this form field a name, like Q for query, let me actually use another HTML attribute called ID, where now I can call this anything I want.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:50.92,2:13:57.55,英文,,0,0,0,,And for clarity, I'm just going to call this input element uniquely name. Now, up here in Query.
Dialogue: 0,2:13:57.55,2:14:09.35,英文,,0,0,0,,query selector, just like in CSS, where you can use hashes and dots and other symbology in order to select certain nodes in your DOM, that is, rectangles in that memory tree.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:09.35,2:14:17.77,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, I can go ahead and select hash name, which, again, is just the syntax for uniquely selecting the element whose ID is, in this case,
Dialogue: 0,2:14:17.77,2:14:19.36,英文,,0,0,0,,So you have the hash up here.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:19.36,2:14:23.78,英文,,0,0,0,,You don't need the hash as the value of the attribute down here on line 20.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:23.78,2:14:28.42,英文,,0,0,0,,And now if I want to actually get the value of that text box, I literally just say dot value.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:28.42,2:14:30.70,英文,,0,0,0,,So document refers to the whole web page itself.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:30.70,2:14:34.60,英文,,0,0,0,,Query selector is a function that's built into that object, so to speak.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:34.60,2:14:45.62,英文,,0,0,0,,And the value, accessible via dot value just like a C struct or even a Python class, allows me to go inside of that text field and get whatever the value the user has typed in.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:45.62,2:14:58.26,英文,,0,0,0,,Now, as I've been able to do in languages like Python fairly readily, I can concatenate this name onto the string hello comma space so as to form a complete phrase.
Dialogue: 0,2:14:58.26,2:15:03.37,英文,,0,0,0,,And you'll notice here that I'm actually using single quotes in my JavaScript, double quotes in my HTML.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:03.37,2:15:05.43,英文,,0,0,0,,This is perhaps a common convention.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:05.43,2:15:09.41,英文,,0,0,0,,In JavaScript, the language does not care if you use double quotes or single quotes.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:09.41,2:15:13.49,英文,,0,0,0,,But I dare say single quotes are just more common. And so that's what I've done here.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:13.49,2:15:16.81,英文,,0,0,0,,All right, now, as always, I'm going to cross my fingers, go back to this page.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:16.81,2:15:21.24,英文,,0,0,0,,I'm going to reload, because I've changed the JavaScript, and I need my browser to download it.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:21.24,2:15:31.17,英文,,0,0,0,,And now I'm going to type in my name, for instance, D-A-V-I-D, click Greets with fingers crossed, and voila, now I see hello, David.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:31.17,2:15:34.87,英文,,0,0,0,,All right, so it turns out that while functional, this isn't the best design.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:34.87,2:15:42.36,英文,,0,0,0,,And commingling your HTML with your JavaScript code, as with this onSubmit attribute, isn't particularly clean.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:42.36,2:15:49.70,英文,,0,0,0,,It's better, as with CSS, to keep your HTML over here, your CSS over here, and your JavaScript now over here, so to speak.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:49.70,2:15:52.54,英文,,0,0,0,,And better still, perhaps even in some separate files.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:52.54,2:15:54.93,英文,,0,0,0,,So how can I go about changing this a little bit?
Dialogue: 0,2:15:54.93,2:15:57.17,英文,,0,0,0,,Well, let me go ahead and actually.
Dialogue: 0,2:15:57.17,2:16:00.53,英文,,0,0,0,,Let's go ahead and delete all of this code for just a moment.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:00.53,2:16:10.28,英文,,0,0,0,,And let me go and get rid of this onSubmit handler down here and really just distill my HTML only into the HTML and the attributes therefore.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:10.28,2:16:13.54,英文,,0,0,0,,And what I'm instead going to do now is do this.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:13.54,2:16:20.74,英文,,0,0,0,,I can use JavaScript to achieve the listening for that submit event or that onSubmit event.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:20.74,2:16:23.30,英文,,0,0,0,,I don't need to actually use HTML for that.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:23.30,2:16:25.56,英文,,0,0,0,,I can use JavaScript entirely.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:25.56,2:16:32.91,英文,,0,0,0,,So it turns out I can access some other member of this document by doing document.querySelector again.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:32.91,2:16:45.70,英文,,0,0,0,,But this time, let's select the actual form tag. And it doesn't have an ID, because it has no ID in its HTML. But it does have a tag name. So just like in CSS, when you can target Elements by way of their name.
Dialogue: 0,2:16:45.70,2:17:00.53,英文,,0,0,0,,I'm just going to select the one and only form on this page by using that same query selector function. And now I'm going to use another function that just comes with JavaScript in the context of browsers, whereby once you select an element like that form, I can call addEventElement.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:00.53,2:17:06.02,英文,,0,0,0,,Listener, which is similar in spirit to Scratch's when green flag clicked or any block like that.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:06.02,2:17:08.78,英文,,0,0,0,,You can then tell the browser what event you want to listen for.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:08.78,2:17:10.56,英文,,0,0,0,,I want to listen for the submit event.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:10.56,2:17:12.18,英文,,0,0,0,,So you don't say on submit here.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:12.18,2:17:14.76,英文,,0,0,0,,Now that we're in pure JavaScript, you just say submit.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:14.76,2:17:17.60,英文,,0,0,0,,And now I can do something like this.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:17.60,2:17:20.77,英文,,0,0,0,,I can go ahead and say, call the following function.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:20.77,2:17:22.87,英文,,0,0,0,,And I'm not even going to bother giving this function a name.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:22.87,2:17:26.52,英文,,0,0,0,,And that is allowed to in JavaScript, as we saw briefly in Python.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:26.52,2:17:33.53,英文,,0,0,0,,And what I'm going to do now inside of curly braces after that keyword function is the same kind of code as before.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:33.53,2:17:38.33,英文,,0,0,0,,I'm going to do let name equals document.querySelector.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:38.33,2:17:44.20,英文,,0,0,0,,I'm going to select that same name ID as before and get its value.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:44.20,2:17:48.58,英文,,0,0,0,,And then I'm going to do alert and then pass in hello, a single quote.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:48.58,2:17:53.85,英文,,0,0,0,,Again, after that, concatenate with that the name, and then Semicolon.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:53.85,2:17:55.57,英文,,0,0,0,,But I need to do one other thing.
Dialogue: 0,2:17:55.57,2:18:04.27,英文,,0,0,0,,It turns out that this function, and if you read the documentation for this technique, actually takes automatically a special argument called by convention event.
Dialogue: 0,2:18:04.27,2:18:08.95,英文,,0,0,0,,And this is just a variable, if you will, that refers to whatever event just happened.
Dialogue: 0,2:18:08.95,2:18:10.91,英文,,0,0,0,,In this case, it's, of course, going to be submit.
Dialogue: 0,2:18:10.91,2:18:15.46,英文,,0,0,0,,But in other contexts, it might be a click event, a mouse down event, or something else entirely.
Dialogue: 0,2:18:15.46,2:18:20.02,英文,,0,0,0,,So this allows me now to do this, which is a little cryptic, but you get used to these conventions.
Dialogue: 0,2:18:20.02,2:18:22.24,英文,,0,0,0,,I can use that event, whatever it is,
